    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If the blockage is only partial, the resulting airspeed indication will be inaccurate, but it won't necessarily drop straight to zero like a complete blockage. Instead, the reading will be artificially low, corresponding to the reduced pressure differential. It's like a goblin trying to carry a giant boulder with only one arm—it's going to move, but it won't move as fast as it should, and it'll probably drop it eventually.\n\nNow, if the **static port** gets blocked, the situation is different and often just as dangerous, though the symptoms might look slightly different depending on the specific instrument design. The static port is supposed to provide the baseline ambient pressure. If it's blocked, the instrument doesn't know what the true surrounding pressure is. The pitot tube might still be capturing the correct total pressure, but without a correct static pressure reference, the calculation for dynamic pressure becomes flawed. The airspeed indicator might show an erratic, fluctuating, or incorrect speed, as the system is comparing a real pressure reading against a false, stagnant one.\n\nIt's like if the goblins were trying to measure the size of a giant mushroom, but only one of the measuring sticks was stuck in the mud—",
